<h2>Step 1 — Choose your contested topic</h2>

<p>Pick one. If you want to propose your own contested scientific topic, talk to Mr. Ignash by Block 3.</p>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Topic</th><th>Why it's contested</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Climate change attribution (how much of recent warming is human-caused?)</td><td>Scientific consensus is strong but communication is contested. Easy to find polarized sources.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Vaccine safety (specifically the long-disproven MMR / autism link)</td><td>Settled science vs. persistent online claims. Great for OPVL on news + AI + social.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>GM crop safety</td><td>Genuine scientific consensus on food safety; legitimate ongoing debate on ecological impact. Surfaces "safe for what?" reasoning.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>AI risk (existential, employment, or near-term harms)</td><td>Active scientific and policy debate. Forces you to OPVL on a topic AI itself has strong opinions about.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Nutritional supplements (one specific product — e.g. melatonin, ashwagandha, vitamin D)</td><td>Industry-funded studies vs. independent reviews. Excellent V/L practice.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Sunscreen safety (chemical vs. mineral; reef safety)</td><td>Two real debates layered. Sources from cosmetics industry, dermatology, marine biology disagree.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Evolution as accepted scientific theory</td><td>Scientific consensus is solid; religious/cultural pushback is the contestation. Different sources frame this very differently.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Nuclear power (climate solution vs. risk)</td><td>Genuine scientific + policy debate. Strong test of cross-source synthesis.</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Step 2 — Find three sources of different types</h2>

<p>You must include at least one source of each type below. The third can be from any category.</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>A traditional reputable source.</strong> Peer-reviewed paper abstract, government agency (USGS, IPCC, WHO, NASA, IMD), or major news outlet (BBC, Reuters, The Hindu, NYT, Nature News).</li>
  <li><strong>A potentially weaker source.</strong> Social media post, corporate communication, industry-funded study, tabloid news, or a TikTok / YouTube video that makes a scientific claim. Note: "weaker" doesn't mean wrong. It means it has different Origins, Purposes, Values, and Limitations than the traditional source.</li>
  <li><strong>An AI source.</strong> Ask an AI (Gemini, Claude, ChatGPT, or a BoodleBox box) to explain your topic. Save the conversation. This is the source you'll OPVL like any other AND document with the AI Documentation Template.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Step 3 — OPVL each source</h2>

<p>For each source, complete the full <a href="/foundations/opvl-framework/">OPVL framework</a> — Origin, Purpose, Value, Limitations. Each OPVL should be 4–8 sentences.</p>

<h2>Step 4 — Cross-source synthesis</h2>

<p>After you've OPVL'd each source individually, write a synthesis section (~300 words) that answers:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Where do the sources agree? Where do they disagree?</li>
  <li>Based on your OPVL of each, which source is most useful for which question?</li>
  <li>What would a person who only read your AI source <strong>not</strong> know that your traditional source covers?</li>
</ul>

<h2>Step 5 — AI Documentation</h2>

<p>Fill out the <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Documentation Template</a> for the AI source. This is not optional. Submit it as a final page of your Dossier or as a separate attachment.</p>

<div class="callout warn">
  <div class="callout-title">Two gates that affect your grade</div>
  <p>If the AI Documentation Template is missing or trivially completed, your <strong>K/U</strong> score cannot exceed 3–4.</p>
  <p>If you can't identify a specific thing the AI got wrong, your <strong>T/T</strong> score cannot exceed 5–6.</p>
  <p>See <a href="/foundations/the-rubric/">the rubric</a> for the full bands.</p>
</div>

<h2>Step 6 — Defend it</h2>

<p>5-minute pitch + 2-minute peer Q&amp;A. Required content for the pitch:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>30-second intro:</strong> your topic + why it's contested</li>
  <li><strong>90 seconds:</strong> walk us through one source — the OPVL move you're proudest of</li>
  <li><strong>90 seconds:</strong> walk us through your AI source — what it got wrong <em>and</em> what it added</li>
  <li><strong>60 seconds:</strong> cross-source synthesis — what would someone miss by only using one of these?</li>
  <li><strong>30 seconds:</strong> what you'd do differently if you had three more sources</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Alternatives (pre-approved by Block 5):</strong> recorded video with the same structure, or written essay (~1200 words). No penalty for choice — same <a href="/foundations/the-rubric/">rubric</a> applies.</p>

<h2>Format guidance</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Written Dossier:</strong> ≤1500 words excluding citations. Google Doc or PDF.</li>
  <li><strong>Video Dossier:</strong> 5–7 min, fully captioned, with on-screen citations.</li>
  <li><strong>Sources:</strong> cite each fully (author, title, source name, date, link). Use any consistent citation style (MLA, APA, Chicago — pick one).</li>
  <li><strong>AI Documentation:</strong> last page of the Dossier or a separate file. Full template fields completed.</li>
</ul>

<h2>How this is scored</h2>

<p>The Source Dossier is scored against the AISC Science strand rubric — three strand scores (K/U / T/T / C) reported as a triplet, not summed. See <a href="/foundations/the-rubric/">The Rubric</a> for the full bands and the two gates above.</p>

